author: Wu Zili
notes: Wu Zili [武自立]. 1994. A preliminary study of the Gasu language of Guangnan County, Yunnan Province [云南省广南县嘎苏话初探]. Minzu Yuwen 2.Kathu (alternatively Kasu or Gasu; autonym: [kᴀ̰33 θṵ31]) is an SOV Lolo-Burmese language spoken in Balong Village (坝聋村), Nanping Township(南屏镇), Guangnan County, Yunnan, China. It has 4 tones, /55/, /33/, /31/, /13/. The subscript tildes signify tenseness, and the apostrophes signify aspiration.Wang Chengyou [王成有]. 2003. A comparative study of Yi dialects [彝语方言比较研究]. Chengdu: Sichuan Ethnic Publishing House [四川民族出版社].According to Chen (2003), this language is spoken by the Flowery Luo (花倮) people of Anwang Village (安王村), Nanping Township (南屏镇), Guangnan County, Yunnan, China. It might be a identical or similar to Kathu as reported in Wu Zili (1994).
